orientation—and at different phases of a parent’s academic career. This collection not only arrives at a comprehensive understanding of parenthood and academia; it reveals the shifting ideologies surrounding the challenges of negotiating work and family balance in this context.  Earlier research on parenting has documented the ways in which women and men experience, and subsequently negotiate, their roles as parents in the context of the workplace and the home. Particular attention has been paid to the negotiation of familial and childcare responsibilities, the division of labour, the availability of family-friendly policies, social constructions of motherhood and fatherhood, power relations, and gender roles and inequality. Studies on the experience of parenthood within the context of academia, however, have lacked diversity and failed to provide qualitative accounts from scholars of all genders at varying points in their academic careers who have, or are planning to have, children. This book addresses that gap.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEducation. 4aFamily & Relationships. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / Parenting / General.2bisacsh  aacademia.  aage.  aagency.  abiological clock.  acareer advancement.  achildless.  achildren.  achoice.  aeducation.  afaculty.  agender.  agraduate studies.  anarratives.  anegotiation.  aparenthood.  aparenting.  apolitics.  arace/ethnicity.  asexual orientation.  astructure.  astruggle.  atenure track.  atenured.  auniversity.  awork -life balance.  awork- family balance.1 aBarker, Jane E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnett, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeaton, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBe